<br>
Not to mince words, but a price, advertised or otherwise, is negotiable by the seller up until the time of sale, esp if its way out of line with what it normally sells for.<br>
<br>
Example, Comp-USA accidentally advertises a 40g HD for .99 instead of $99. People rush the store to buy it. They can *legally* at the time of sale say, sorry, the price is $99, the ad was a typo.<br>
<br>
Now, if a clerk doesn't pay attention and in fact sells the product for $0.99, there is no recourse to obtain the item UNLESS it was sold under false pretense (ie, I switched the sticker from a trinket to the HD).<br>
<br>
A good example of that is an e-commerce vendor who miss priced a 19&quot; monitor for an insane price many years ago. Over 100 people paid for the monitor and had electronic proof of the transaction. After much broohaha the vendor was required to honor the purchase.<br>
<br>
Point being, up until you actually exchange money for the product, UNLESS in a valid written contract, the price can change and the buyer has very little legal recourse. There are, of course, exceptions to that legaleze I just walked through but that is generally the rule of law in these matters. <p><html>

